TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper examines the effects of changes in financial disclosure mandated by the Securities Act of 1933 on the distribution of returns earned by investors in new stock issues. The existence of substantial uncertainty about the true value of a security need not imply that the issue will be, however, affect the riskiness of the purchase. Findings show that mean returns were not changed by regulation in markets with low information costs. The dispersion of abnormal returns (investors' forecast errors) was significantly lower following the Securities Act, however.
AU  - Simon, Carol J.
